I'll help modify the `launchCameraOnDevice` function to use the placeholder image when running on an emulator. Here's the updated code:

```typescript:src/pages/user-registration/screens/user-registration.screen.4.tsx
// ... existing code ...
const launchCameraOnDevice = async () => {
  try {
    const isEmulator = await DeviceInfo.isEmulator();
    let res = undefined;
    if (isEmulator) {
      res = {
        assets: [{
          uri: PLACEHOLDER_PHOTO_URL
        }]
      }
    } else {
      res = await launchCamera({mediaType: 'photo'})
    }
    setImage(res)
    console.log(image)
    setUrlName(
      `${PFP_URL}u_${userProvider.email
      .replaceAll('@', '%40')
      .replaceAll('.', '%2E')}`
    )
    console.log(urlName)
  } catch (error) {
    handleDocPickerError(error)
  }
}
// ... existing code ...
```

The changes:
1. When `isEmulator` is true, we now set `res` to an object that matches the structure expected by the image display code
2. The object contains an `assets` array with a single item containing the `uri` property set to `PLACEHOLDER_PHOTO_URL`
3. This matches the structure that would normally come from `launchCamera()` but uses our placeholder image instead

This will allow the Avatar component to display the placeholder image when running on an emulator, while still using the camera on physical devices.

